{
    "publish_date": "2011-12-08T20:15:14.000Z", 
    "video_length": "PT4M26S", 
    "captions": [
        {
            "text": "So you&#39;re me and\nyou&#39;re in math class", 
            "dur": "1.23", 
            "start": "0.15"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and-- triangles, triangles,\ntriangles-- I don&#39;t know.", 
            "dur": "1.58", 
            "start": "1.38"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The teacher keeps\nsaying words, and you&#39;re", 
            "dur": "1.099", 
            "start": "2.96"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "supposed to be doing\nsomething with trigons,", 
            "dur": "1.491", 
            "start": "4.059"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "whatever those are.", 
            "dur": "0.67", 
            "start": "5.55"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But you&#39;re bored and--\ntriangles, triangles,", 
            "dur": "1.44", 
            "start": "6.22"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "triangles.", 
            "dur": "0.5", 
            "start": "7.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Sure you could draw your\ntriangles separately,", 
            "dur": "1.97", 
            "start": "8.16"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but then they get lonely.", 
            "dur": "0.76", 
            "start": "10.13"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "They&#39;re happiest when\nsnuggled up together", 
            "dur": "1.28", 
            "start": "10.89"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "into a triangle party.", 
            "dur": "0.916", 
            "start": "12.17"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Everybody knows\ntriangles love parties.", 
            "dur": "1.734", 
            "start": "13.086"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Sometimes they get together and\ndo these triangle congo lines.", 
            "dur": "2.13", 
            "start": "14.82"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you keep adding new\ntriangles on the same side,", 
            "dur": "1.81", 
            "start": "16.95"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "it gets all curvy and spirally.", 
            "dur": "1.25", 
            "start": "18.76"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or you can alternate and\nit goes pretty straight.", 
            "dur": "1.87", 
            "start": "20.01"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, since all the\nsides of the triangle", 
            "dur": "1.82", 
            "start": "21.88"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "are supposed to\nbe straight lines,", 
            "dur": "1.03", 
            "start": "23.7"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and since they&#39;re\nall lying on top", 
            "dur": "0.74", 
            "start": "24.73"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of some previous straight\nline, then this whole line", 
            "dur": "2.19", 
            "start": "25.47"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "would have to be straight if\nthese were actually triangles.", 
            "dur": "2.458", 
            "start": "27.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Since it&#39;s not, it&#39;s proof that\nthese aren&#39;t quite triangles.", 
            "dur": "2.702", 
            "start": "30.118"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Maybe they&#39;ve been\npartying a little too hard,", 
            "dur": "1.37", 
            "start": "32.82"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but hey, at least\nyou&#39;re not doing math.", 
            "dur": "1.93", 
            "start": "34.19"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Speaking of which,\nthe teacher is still", 
            "dur": "1.15", 
            "start": "36.12"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "going on about types\nof trigons, and you&#39;re", 
            "dur": "1.51", 
            "start": "37.27"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "supposed to be taking notes.", 
            "dur": "0.91", 
            "start": "38.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But you&#39;re more\ninteresting in types", 
            "dur": "0.992", 
            "start": "39.69"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of triangles, which you\nalready know all about.", 
            "dur": "2.018", 
            "start": "40.682"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "There are fat triangles,\nand pointy triangles,", 
            "dur": "1.68", 
            "start": "42.7"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and perfect\ntriangles, and cheese", 
            "dur": "1.09", 
            "start": "44.38"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "slice triangles which are\na kind of pointy triangle", 
            "dur": "1.86", 
            "start": "45.47"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but are symmetric like a\nslice of cheese or cake.", 
            "dur": "2.099", 
            "start": "47.33"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Super pointy triangles are fun\nto stack into triangle stacks.", 
            "dur": "2.541", 
            "start": "49.429"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can put all the points\nfacing one direction,", 
            "dur": "1.73", 
            "start": "51.97"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but the stack starts\nto wobble too much", 
            "dur": "1.21", 
            "start": "53.7"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "towards that direction.", 
            "dur": "0.93", 
            "start": "54.91"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So it&#39;s good to put some facing\nthe other direction before you", 
            "dur": "1.78", 
            "start": "55.84"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "go too far.", 
            "dur": "0.5", 
            "start": "57.62"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You&#39;ll notice pretty quickly,\nthat the skinnier the triangle,", 
            "dur": "2.541", 
            "start": "58.12"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the less wobble it\nadds to the stack.", 
            "dur": "1.619", 
            "start": "60.661"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "To compensate for\na big wobble, you", 
            "dur": "1.34", 
            "start": "62.28"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "can put just one not\nso skinny triangle", 
            "dur": "1.6", 
            "start": "63.62"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that&#39;s pointing the other way.", 
            "dur": "0.98", 
            "start": "65.22"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or maybe you want to\nwobble, because you", 
            "dur": "1.36", 
            "start": "66.2"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "have to navigate your triangle\nstack around your notes.", 
            "dur": "1.93", 
            "start": "67.56"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In which case you can even\nalternate back and forth", 
            "dur": "1.72", 
            "start": "69.49"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "as long as you make the\ntriangles point towards where", 
            "dur": "1.69", 
            "start": "71.21"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you want to go, a\nlittle less skinny.", 
            "dur": "1.63", 
            "start": "72.9"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The easy part about\ntriangle stacks,", 
            "dur": "1.5", 
            "start": "74.53"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "is that there&#39;s really only\none part of the triangle that&#39;s", 
            "dur": "2.01", 
            "start": "76.03"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "important, as far as\nthe stack is concerned.", 
            "dur": "1.9", 
            "start": "78.04"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And that&#39;s the pointy point.", 
            "dur": "1.26", 
            "start": "79.94"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The other two angles can be fat\nand skinny, or skinny and fat,", 
            "dur": "2.13", 
            "start": "81.2"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "or both the same if\nit&#39;s a cheese slice,", 
            "dur": "1.6", 
            "start": "83.33"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and it doesn&#39;t change\nthe rest of the stack.", 
            "dur": "1.77", 
            "start": "84.93"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Unless the top angle\nis really wide,", 
            "dur": "1.49", 
            "start": "86.7"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because then you&#39;ll\nget two skinny points,", 
            "dur": "1.4", 
            "start": "88.19"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and which side should\nyou continue to stack on?", 
            "dur": "1.79", 
            "start": "89.59"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Both?", 
            "dur": "0.47", 
            "start": "91.38"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Also, instead of\nthinking fat and skinny,", 
            "dur": "1.52", 
            "start": "91.85"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you should probably\ncreate code words", 
            "dur": "1.29", 
            "start": "93.37"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "that won&#39;t set off your\nteacher&#39;s mind reading", 
            "dur": "1.916", 
            "start": "94.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "alarms for non-math\nrelated thoughts.", 
            "dur": "1.565", 
            "start": "96.576"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So you pick two words off\nthe board, obtuse and acute,", 
            "dur": "2.249", 
            "start": "98.141"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which by sheer\ncoincidence I&#39;m sure, just", 
            "dur": "1.75", 
            "start": "100.39"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "happen to mean fat\nangle and skinny angle.", 
            "dur": "1.98", 
            "start": "102.14"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Of course, those are\nalso kinds of triangles.", 
            "dur": "1.91", 
            "start": "104.12"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Which doesn&#39;t make much\nsense, because the obtuser one", 
            "dur": "1.86", 
            "start": "106.03"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "angle of a triangle is, the\nmore acute the other two get.", 
            "dur": "2.375", 
            "start": "107.89"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Yet, if you make\nan acute triangle", 
            "dur": "1.416", 
            "start": "110.265"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with the same perimeter,\nit has more area,", 
            "dur": "1.889", 
            "start": "111.681"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "which seems like\nan obtuse quality.", 
            "dur": "2.007", 
            "start": "113.57"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And then, can you still\ncall an obtuse equilateral", 
            "dur": "2.083", 
            "start": "115.577"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "triangle a cheese or\ncake-slice triangle,", 
            "dur": "1.84", 
            "start": "117.66"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "because these look\nmore like [INAUDIBLE].", 
            "dur": "1.93", 
            "start": "119.5"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Point is, triangle\nterminology is tricky,", 
            "dur": "1.91", 
            "start": "121.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "but at least you&#39;re not\npaying attention to the stuff", 
            "dur": "1.71", 
            "start": "123.34"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the teacher is saying about\ntrigonometric functions.", 
            "dur": "2.38", 
            "start": "125.05"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You&#39;d rather think about\nthe functions of triangles.", 
            "dur": "1.93", 
            "start": "127.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And you already\nknow some of those.", 
            "dur": "1.458", 
            "start": "129.36"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "There are sines, and cosines,\nbut enough of this tangent.", 
            "dur": "3.556", 
            "start": "130.818"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The thing to pay attention to is\nwhat affects your triangle how.", 
            "dur": "2.666", 
            "start": "134.374"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you start drawing the next\ntriangle on your triangle", 
            "dur": "2.12", 
            "start": "137.04"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "stack this way, by\nthis point, you already", 
            "dur": "1.8", 
            "start": "139.16"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "know what the full\ntriangle would have to be.", 
            "dur": "1.74", 
            "start": "140.96"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Because you just continue\nthis edge until it", 
            "dur": "1.49", 
            "start": "142.7"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "meets this invisible line,\nand then fill the rest in.", 
            "dur": "2.39", 
            "start": "144.19"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "In fact, you can make an\nentire triangle stack just", 
            "dur": "2.219", 
            "start": "146.58"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "by piling on triangle parts\nand adding the points later", 
            "dur": "2.291", 
            "start": "148.799"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to see what happens.", 
            "dur": "0.97", 
            "start": "151.09"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "There&#39;s some possible\nproblems though.", 
            "dur": "1.714", 
            "start": "152.06"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "If you start a\ntriangle like this,", 
            "dur": "1.416", 
            "start": "153.774"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you can see that it&#39;s never\ngoing to close, no matter", 
            "dur": "2.208", 
            "start": "155.19"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "how far you extend the lines.", 
            "dur": "1.282", 
            "start": "157.398"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Since this triangle\nisn&#39;t real, let&#39;s", 
            "dur": "1.6", 
            "start": "158.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "call it a Bermuda Triangle.", 
            "dur": "1.56", 
            "start": "160.28"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "This happens when\ntwo angles together", 
            "dur": "1.67", 
            "start": "161.84"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "are already more\nthan 180 degrees.", 
            "dur": "1.557", 
            "start": "163.51"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And since all the\nangles in a triangle", 
            "dur": "1.583", 
            "start": "165.067"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "add up to 180--\nwhich, by the way,", 
            "dur": "1.79", 
            "start": "166.65"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you can test by ripping one\nup and putting the three", 
            "dur": "1.57", 
            "start": "168.44"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "points into a line-- that\nmeans that if these are", 
            "dur": "2.12", 
            "start": "170.01"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "two 120 degree\nangles of a triangle,", 
            "dur": "1.86", 
            "start": "172.13"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the third angle is off\nsomewhere being negative 60.", 
            "dur": "2.929", 
            "start": "173.99"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Of course, you have no problem\nbeing a Bermuda Triangle", 
            "dur": "2.291", 
            "start": "176.919"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "on a sphere, were angles\nalways add up to more than 180,", 
            "dur": "2.72", 
            "start": "179.21"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "just the third point\nmight be off in Australia.", 
            "dur": "2.28", 
            "start": "181.93"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Which is fine, unless you&#39;re\nafraid your triangle might", 
            "dur": "2.291", 
            "start": "184.21"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "get eaten by sea monsters.", 
            "dur": "1.089", 
            "start": "186.501"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Anyway, stacking triangles\ninto a curve is nice,", 
            "dur": "2.02", 
            "start": "187.59"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and you probably want\nto make a spiral.", 
            "dur": "1.624", 
            "start": "189.61"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "But if you&#39;re not careful,\nit&#39;ll crash into itself.", 
            "dur": "2.196", 
            "start": "191.234"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So you&#39;d better think\nabout your angles.", 
            "dur": "1.35", 
            "start": "193.43"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Though, if you do it just right,\ninstead of a crash disaster,", 
            "dur": "2.07", 
            "start": "194.78"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "you&#39;ll get a wreath thing.", 
            "dur": "1.11", 
            "start": "196.85"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Or you can get a\ndifferent triangle circle", 
            "dur": "1.75", 
            "start": "197.96"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "by starting with a polygon,\nextending the sides in one", 
            "dur": "2.19", 
            "start": "199.71"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "direction, and then\ntriangling around it,", 
            "dur": "1.6", 
            "start": "201.9"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to get this sort\nof aperture shape.", 
            "dur": "1.42", 
            "start": "203.5"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And then you should\nprobably add more triangles,", 
            "dur": "1.56", 
            "start": "204.92"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "triangles, triangles--", 
            "dur": "1.16", 
            "start": "206.48"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "One last game.", 
            "dur": "0.82", 
            "start": "207.64"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Start with some\nsort of asterisk,", 
            "dur": "1.52", 
            "start": "208.46"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "then go around a triangle it up.", 
            "dur": "1.432", 
            "start": "209.98"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Shade out from the\nobtusest angles,", 
            "dur": "1.458", 
            "start": "211.412"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and it&#39;ll look pretty neat.", 
            "dur": "0.85", 
            "start": "212.87"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can then extend it with\nanother layer of triangles,", 
            "dur": "1.88", 
            "start": "213.72"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and another, and if you\nshade the inner parts", 
            "dur": "1.6", 
            "start": "215.6"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of these triangles,\nit&#39;s guaranteed", 
            "dur": "0.985", 
            "start": "217.2"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to be an awesome triangle party.", 
            "dur": "1.665", 
            "start": "218.185"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "And there&#39;s lots of other\nkinds of triangle parties just", 
            "dur": "1.97", 
            "start": "219.85"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "waiting to happen.", 
            "dur": "0.749", 
            "start": "221.82"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Ah, the triangle.", 
            "dur": "1.141", 
            "start": "222.569"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "So simple, yet so beautiful.", 
            "dur": "1.244", 
            "start": "223.71"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "The essence of\ntwo-dimensionality,", 
            "dur": "1.416", 
            "start": "224.954"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the fundamental object\nof Euclidean geometry,", 
            "dur": "2.369", 
            "start": "226.37"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "the three points\nthat define a plane.", 
            "dur": "1.541", 
            "start": "228.739"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "You can have your\nfancy complex shapes,", 
            "dur": "1.69", 
            "start": "230.28"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "they&#39;re just made\nup of triangles.", 
            "dur": "2.06", 
            "start": "231.97"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Triangles.", 
            "dur": "0.86", 
            "start": "234.03"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Dissect a square into triangles,\nmake symmetric arrangements,", 
            "dur": "2.08", 
            "start": "234.89"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "some reminiscent of spherical\nand hyperbolic geometry.", 
            "dur": "2.29", 
            "start": "236.97"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Triangles branches into\nbinary fractal trees.", 
            "dur": "2.12", 
            "start": "239.26"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Numbers increasing exponentially\nwith each iteration", 
            "dur": "2.24", 
            "start": "241.38"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to infinity.", 
            "dur": "0.93", 
            "start": "243.62"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Triangles, with the\nright proportion", 
            "dur": "1.5", 
            "start": "244.55"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "being a golden spiral of perfect\nright isosceles triangles.", 
            "dur": "2.93", 
            "start": "246.05"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "Put equilateral triangles\non the middle third", 
            "dur": "1.9", 
            "start": "248.98"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "of the outside edges of\nequilateral triangles", 
            "dur": "1.8", 
            "start": "250.88"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "to infinity, and\nget a snow flake", 
            "dur": "1.26", 
            "start": "252.68"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "with the boundary\nof the Koch Curve.", 
            "dur": "1.32", 
            "start": "253.94"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "An infinitely long perimeter,\ncontinuous yet nowhere", 
            "dur": "2.31", 
            "start": "255.26"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "differentiable.", 
            "dur": "0.625", 
            "start": "257.57"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "With a fractional dimension\nof log four over log three,", 
            "dur": "2.584", 
            "start": "258.195"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "and-- uh oh, teacher&#39;s\nwalking around,", 
            "dur": "1.841", 
            "start": "260.779"
        }, 
        {
            "text": "better pretend to be doing math.", 
            "dur": "2.4", 
            "start": "262.62"
        }
    ], 
